beginning, after the war, he used to take children to school, to different schools and he used to take maladjusted children around and take them to camps for their holidays and things like that. And now he drives around taking food to old people, and take
s them for a weeks holiday somewhere. And he's highly political, much more than me. All his family is in fact. And he - he even marched with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12472523\charrsid3955477 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10507726\charrsid3955477 arrow marchers, he's don}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12472523\charrsid3955477 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10507726\charrsid3955477 
 everything, 'cos they really knew what poverty was, they knew about it in Glasgow and
 Scotland, and you know the time of the strike in 1926 was a terrible time for them, they didn't have anything to put on their feet or no food and they were twelve children in his family, ten boys. And so therefore he's really adamant about his politics.

